{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01SEi5f18bqTrvg62xvYkzAT","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the framework provided.\n\n**Behavior 1**: A file placed inside a subdirectory of the watched root is processed, not only files placed directly in the root directory.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about whether the watcher is configured to watch recursively. This could be a unit test checking watcher configuration, but the real failure is whether the OS actually delivers events for subdirectory files. This is an integration/system concern.\n- REAL-INFRA: The behavior depends on real filesystem events from a real OS filesystem watcher (like inotify, FSEvents, etc.). Could a fake filesystem reproduce this? It depends - some watchers use in-process abstractions. \n\nThe core issue is that recursive watching behavior ultimately relies on actual OS filesystem events, not just configuration. Even if the daemon sets the recursive flag correctly, a mock filesystem watcher would pass regardless of whether the OS actually delivers those nested events. This is fundamentally a system test that needs real filesystem events to catch configuration failures.\n\nFor deduplication, I'm looking at a pure algorithmic concern—whether the logic correctly filters duplicate requests within a time window. This doesn't depend on OS or network infrastructure, just in-process timers and timestamps, so it's a unit test candidate using fake timers to control the time window.\n\nNow for the third behavior: the key distinction is that the OS itself emits multiple events for a single file write.  I could inject multiple events through a fake watcher to test the deduplication logic, but the behavior explicitly depends on real OS event patterns. The question is whether mocking multiple events would actually catch the failure or just hide it—if the real OS emits events in a way the mock doesn't replicate, the test could pass with a mock but fail in production. the integration actually works with real OS events. So behavior 3 should test whether the deduplication logic handles whatever the real filesystem throws at it, not just a controlled set of mock events. But I'm second-guessing myself—if a stub can emit multiple events just like the OS would, then behavior 2 and 3 blur together. The real distinction might be that behavior 3 specifically validates the end-to-end flow with actual filesystem behavior, whereas behavior 2 just tests the deduplication logic in isolation. with behavior 2 since both involve processing once, but behavior 3's specific angle is handling OS-level event storms—I can test this with in-process fakes by firing multiple events for the same file in quick succession and verifying the daemon only processes it once, making this an integration test.\n\nFor behavior 4, when a watched directory gets deleted and recreated while the daemon runs, it needs to resume watching without restarting. This is a real filesystem interaction—the OS watcher will emit a delete event and stop, then the daemon needs to detect the new directory and re-register with the OS.\n\nA fake watcher could simulate the sequence of deletion and recreation events, but the real complexity is whether the actual OS watcher (inotify, FSEvents, etc.) fires these events in the expected order and whether the daemon properly catches them to set up a new watcher. This is OS-dependent behavior that requires real filesystem operations, so it's a system-level test.\n\nFor behavior 5, I'm looking at whether multiple files arriving simultaneously get processed in the order of their creation timestamps—this could be tested as a unit test of the sorting logic itself. integration of how files are queued and processed.\n- REAL-INFRA: \"Arrive at the same time\" with real filesystem might have timestamp precision issues. The ordering logic itself is deterministic (sort by creation timestamp). But creation timestamps on real filesystems might have limited precision (millisecond or second granularity), making files created \"at the same time\" have identical timestamps.\n- The behavior is testing whether files are processed in timestamp order. The sorting logic could be unit-tested. But \"arrive at the same time\" suggests real filesystem files with real timestamps.\n- Actually, I think this is Integration - you create multiple files with known timestamps (or use a fake/mock that provides timestamps), wire the pipeline together, and verify processing order. The failure is in how the queuing and ordering logic work together.\n- If files arrive with identical timestamps, the ordering becomes undefined. For the test, I'd create multiple files with forced different timestamps using filesystem mocking, then verify they're processed in the right order. This is definitely an integration test where the watcher, queue, and processor all work together.\n\nNow looking at behavior 6: a file that's still being written to shouldn't be picked up until the write completes. This is about detecting file completeness.\n- REAL-INFRA: Detecting write completion is a genuine OS/filesystem challenge. The daemon needs real mechanisms like file lock checking, polling for stable file size, or waiting for file close events. These depend on actual OS APIs and behavior.\n- The failure mode is the daemon picking up a partial file. To reproduce this, one process writes while another tries to read before the write finishes - this requires real filesystem operations.\n- This is System level because it depends on real OS behavior and file handles.\n\nI'm reconsidering behavior 6 - the mechanism to detect \"writing is complete\" could involve polling for stable file size or...\n\nWatching for file close events, trying to get an exclusive lock, or using a sentinel file. Polling could be faked with a mock filesystem simulating size changes, but the real timing of \"file still being written\" is tricky to mock. File close events and locking depend on actual OS behavior across processes, so those mechanisms are inherently System level.\n\nGiven that detecting \"a file still being written\" involves real OS process-level file operations, the failure only manifests with real OS file locking or event delivery.\n\nSo behavior 1 is System level - requires real OS filesystem events for nested directories. Behavior 2 is Unit level - pure deduplication logic testable with...\n\nNow I'm mapping out the test approach for each behavior. System tests need real filesystem operations and OS watchers. Unit tests use fake timers to test deduplication directly. Integration tests simulate multiple events through wired modules. System tests for directory removal use real filesystem lifecycle events. Integration tests create files with known timestamps to verify ordering through the pipeline. And behavior 6 requires real OS file write and lock detection, so that's System level too. timers control time advancement. Now I'm realizing behaviors 2 and 3 overlap—both test deduplication of repeated file paths, but behavior 2 isolates the deduplication function itself while behavior 3 tests it integrated with the event pipeline. The key distinction is whether I'm testing the pure logic in isolation or how it responds to actual event emissions from the watcher.\n\nBehavior 4 requires real OS filesystem operations since the daemon needs to detect when a watched directory is deleted and re-register a watcher after it's recreated—something a mock can't authentically simulate.\n\nFor behavior 5, I'm setting up a test that injects file events directly into the processing queue...\n\nBehavior 5 tests timestamp-based ordering across the watcher-to-processor pipeline, which is purely algorithmic and doesn't depend on OS behavior, so it fits at the Integration level.\n\nBehavior 6 needs real OS file locking mechanisms to verify the daemon won't process a file while another process still has it open—mocks can't replicate actual file handle states.\n\nNow I'm assigning probability distributions across test levels for each behavior. Behavior 1 (recursive watching) is most likely a System-level concern since the OS handles directory recursion. Behavior 2 (deduplication) is clearly Unit-testable logic with high confidence. Behavior 3 (multiple events debounced to single processing) sits mostly at Integration since it requires wiring event sources together, though the debounce function itself could be tested in isolation.\n\nBehavior 4 (directory removal and recreation) is almost certainly System-level—real filesystem operations are needed. Behavior 5 (ordering by creation timestamp) is primarily Integration-level since it involves wiring the queue with timestamp logic, though the sorting algorithm itself is Unit-testable. Behavior 6 (detecting files still being written) is another System-level concern because it depends on real OS file handles and locking mechanisms.\n\nFor behavior 3, I'm reconsidering whether the OS event multiplicity can be tested without a real filesystem. If the daemon uses debouncing—waiting 100ms before processing—I could emit multiple events through a fake in-process event emitter and advance fake timers to verify it processes only once. That would be Integration-level. The real OS triggers the event storm, but the defense mechanism itself can be validated without real OS behavior. The question is whether the deduplication logic is actually being tested or if I'm just testing the debouncing mechanism in isolation.\n\nFor behavior 5, I'm looking at how files with identical creation timestamps get ordered. On real filesystems, timestamp precision might be limited, so multiple files created simultaneously could have the same timestamp. The test would need to either control timestamps explicitly or understand how the daemon breaks ties when timestamps are equal.\n\nMy final assessment: behaviors 1, 4, and 6 need System-level tests, while behaviors 2, 3, and 5 work at the Integration level.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":12748,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":12748},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5bcad727-cd0e-4dee-be4f-ed61a96db0b8","uuid":"1fa3d345-e1af-4fdc-8bce-fb0a3a9951b9"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01SEi5f18bqTrvg62xvYkzAT","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01BXiktKfeuchhrjcUd3PRcT","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"A file placed inside a subdirectory of the watched root is processed, not only files placed directly in the root directory.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"REAL-INFRA: Recursive directory watching is handled differently by each OS watcher backend (inotify on Linux, FSEvents on macOS, ReadDirectoryChangesW on Windows). Whether the watcher is configured with the recursive flag and whether the OS actually delivers events for nested paths is a real OS concern. An in-process fake watcher would simply emit an event for any path you tell it to, bypassing the real failure: the daemon's watcher was not set up recursively or the OS did not propagate events through subdirectory boundaries. REJECTION-GATE: There is no text in the behavior disqualifying System. The behavior explicitly concerns a real filesystem path hierarchy that only the OS watcher resolves correctly.","test_description":"Spin up the daemon against a real temporary directory. Create a nested subdirectory (e.g., watched/sub/deep/) using real OS mkdir calls. Drop a file into the deepest subdirectory. Assert that the transformation pipeline runs and the output file appears in the output directory. No files placed at the root level are used, so any result confirms recursive watching rather than flat watching.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.13,"System":0.75,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The deduplication logic correctly discards a second processing request for the same file path within a configurable time window.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure is entirely within one module's logic: a data structure (e.g., a Map or Set) keyed by file path with a TTL, compared against the current time. There is no multi-module handoff whose boundary could hide the bug. REAL-INFRA: No OS, network, or real filesystem is involved. Fake timers (e.g., Jest's jest.useFakeTimers) can advance the clock deterministically to test within-window discard and post-window acceptance. LLM-DEP: No AI involved. REJECTION-GATE: Nothing in the behavior requires real infrastructure; the configurable time window is a pure numeric parameter and the deduplication is a pure in-memory algorithm.","test_description":"Isolate the deduplication module. Install fake timers. Call the deduplication entry point twice with the same file path within the configured window; assert the processor callback fires exactly once. Advance fake time past the window; submit the same path again; assert the processor fires a second time, confirming the TTL expired correctly.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.74,"Integration":0.21,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When the operating system emits multiple filesystem events for a single file write, the daemon processes the file exactly once.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure is at the boundary between the event ingestion layer and the deduplication/debounce layer. A unit test of the debounce function alone (behavior 2) does not verify that the event listener correctly feeds duplicates into the debounce gate. The failure appears only when the two modules are wired together. REAL-INFRA: The OS event storm is a trigger, but the daemon's defense—debouncing or coalescing—operates on whatever events arrive, regardless of source. An in-process event emitter can faithfully simulate rapid-fire duplicate events; the failure mode ('processed more than once') is fully reproducible without a real filesystem. REJECTION-GATE: The behavior says 'the daemon processes the file exactly once'—this is a claim about the daemon's internal event-handling pipeline, not about OS-specific event characteristics. The OS event storm motivation does not require a real OS to test the daemon's response to it.","test_description":"Wire the real watcher event emitter to the real deduplication and processor modules (using an in-process test harness). Emit three rapid 'add'/'change' events for the same file path through the watcher's event interface without touching a real filesystem. Assert the processor callback is invoked exactly once after the debounce settle period (controlled via fake timers). Also assert that if the same path is later emitted after the window, the processor fires again.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.3,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"If the watched directory is removed and then recreated while the daemon is running, the daemon resumes watching the new directory without a restart.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"REAL-INFRA: OS watchers (inotify, FSEvents) behave differently when a watched inode is unlinked versus when a directory is renamed away. Whether the daemon receives a deletion event, whether the watcher handle becomes invalid, and whether re-registering on the new inode at the same path works correctly are all OS-level behaviors. A mock watcher would simply emit synthetic 'unlink' and 're-add' events, but the real failure is that OS watcher handles become stale after directory removal and the daemon must detect this and re-register with the real OS. An in-process fake cannot replicate inode lifecycle. REJECTION-GATE: The behavior says 'if the watched directory is removed and then recreated'—this is a real OS directory lifecycle operation with no text limiting it to in-process simulation.","test_description":"Start the daemon against a real temporary directory. Use real OS calls (fs.rmSync with recursive) to delete the watched directory. Wait for the daemon's recovery logic to fire (poll for watcher re-registration). Use real OS mkdir to recreate the directory at the same path. Drop a real file into the recreated directory. Assert the output file appears, confirming the daemon resumed watching the new inode without a process restart.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.85,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When multiple files arrive at the same time, they are processed in the order determined by their creation timestamps.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure lives at the boundary between the arrival queue and the processor: the queue must sort by timestamp before dispatching, and the processor must receive them in that order. A unit test of a sort function does not verify that timestamps are correctly read from file metadata and fed into the queue, nor that the queue respects the sort before calling the processor. REAL-INFRA: The sorting algorithm is deterministic given timestamps. Timestamps can be provided by stubbing fs.stat (or equivalent) to return controlled birthtimeMs values, making real filesystem unnecessary. The in-process stub fully reproduces the failure mode ('files processed out of timestamp order'). REJECTION-GATE: Nothing in the behavior requires real filesystem timestamps; 'creation timestamps' is metadata the daemon reads, and that read can be stubbed.","test_description":"Wire the watcher event emitter, the arrival queue, and the processor together in a test harness. Stub fs.stat (using patch.object equivalent in Node: jest.spyOn(fs.promises, 'stat')) to return three different birthtimeMs values assigned out-of-arrival-order to three file paths. Emit all three arrival events in a burst. Assert the processor receives the three files in ascending birthtimeMs order, regardless of emission order.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.17,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"A file that is still being written to when the arrival event fires is not picked up for processing until writing is complete.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"REAL-INFRA: Detecting whether a file is still open for writing requires real OS primitives. Strategies like polling for stable file size, attempting an exclusive open (O_EXCL or LOCK_EX), or waiting for a close/rename event all depend on real OS file handle and locking semantics. A fake filesystem cannot faithfully simulate 'another process holds an exclusive write handle'—it can emit a flag, but that bypasses the actual OS mechanism the daemon relies on. The failure mode ('daemon reads a partial file') only appears when a real write handle is open in another process. REJECTION-GATE: The behavior says 'a file that is still being written to'—this is inherently a real OS cross-process file handle condition with no text limiting it to in-process simulation.","test_description":"Start the daemon against a real temporary directory. In the test, spawn a real child process (or use fs.createWriteStream without closing it) that holds an open write handle to a file in the watched directory. Allow the arrival event to fire. Assert that the processor has not been called (the file is still open). Then close the write handle. Assert that the processor is called within the daemon's polling interval and that the output file contains complete, non-truncated content.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.85,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":12748,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephem